# InsightFlow AI Requirements Document

## 1. Application Overview

### 1.1 Application Name
InsightFlow AI\n
### 1.2 Application Description
InsightFlow AI is an advanced all-in-one platform for Data Analytics, Data Science, SQL, Python, Machine Learning, and Data Modeling designed specifically for students and professionals. The platform enables users to upload unlimited datasets, preview and manage them through an intuitive Table View, perform comprehensive data cleaning with dataset selection capabilities, create advanced visualizations including KPI cards, build interactive dashboards with fully resizable charts, and train machine learning models with intelligent recommendations. A key differentiator is the fully functional SQL Editor and Python Editor where any operation performed on a dataset—such as filtering, updating, deleting rows, adding columns, merging datasets, grouping, or transforming values—directly modifies the actual stored data, ensuring all changes reflect across Visualization, ML Studio, Dashboard, and Reports modules. The Data Modeling module supports joining unlimited tables with visual and SQL-based interfaces. Additionally, users can view video tutorials and demonstrations directly within the platform. The application operates without authentication requirements, allowing immediate access to all features.\n
## 2. Data Management

### 2.1 Browser-Based Storage

**Data Persistence:**
- All uploaded datasets stored in browser LocalStorage or IndexedDB
- Cleaned data versions saved automatically in browser storage
- Created charts and dashboards saved to browser storage
- Trained ML models and reports stored in browser workspace
- User preferences and settings stored in browser\n- SQL queries and Python scripts saved per session
- Data modeling configurations and join relationships stored locally
- All SQL and Python operations update the actual stored dataset in browser
- Video viewing history and bookmarks stored in browser

**Data Management:**
- View all uploaded datasets in dashboard
- Delete datasets when no longer needed
- Access history of data cleaning operations
- Manage saved charts and dashboards
- Download or share saved visualizations
- Organize datasets into project folders
- Data persists across browser sessions until manually cleared

### 2.2 Project Management & Organization

**Project Folder System:**
- Create unlimited project folders to organize datasets
- Rename project folders\n- Move datasets between folders
- Delete entire project folders (with confirmation)
- Each project folder contains:\n  - Multiple datasets
  - Associated visualizations
  - Dashboards
  - ML models and reports
  - SQL queries\n  - Python scripts
  - Data modeling configurations
\n**Dataset Management (Unlimited Upload & Full Control):**
- Upload unlimited datasets per project
- Preview dataset contents before processing:\n  - View first100 rows of data
  - Inspect column names, data types, and sample values
  - Check dataset statistics (row count, column count, missing values)
- Modify dataset metadata:\n  - Edit dataset name and add description
  - Add tags for easy searching
  - Update column names and properties
- Delete individual datasets with confirmation
- Duplicate datasets for experimentation
- View detailed dataset schema information
- Export datasets in various formats\n
**New Data Upload Behavior with Workspace Reset Confirmation:**
- When user attempts to upload new dataset(s) to current working session, system displays confirmation dialog:\n  - Dialog Title: 'Reset Workspace?'
  - Dialog Message: 'Uploading new dataset(s) will clear all current charts, dashboards, and ML reports. Your current project will be saved and can be accessed from the Previous Projects section on the home page.'
  - Dialog Options:
    - 'Save & Continue' button: Saves current project to Previous Projects and proceeds with new upload
    - 'Cancel' button: Cancels upload and returns to current workspace
- If user confirms'Save & Continue':
  - Current project is automatically saved with all charts, dashboards, and ML reports
  - Saved project appears in Previous Projects section
  - All current session content is reset:\n    - All existing charts are cleared
    - All dashboards are cleared
    - All ML models and reports are cleared
    - Data cleaning history is cleared
  - User starts with fresh workspace for new dataset\n- If user cancels, current workspace remains unchanged

**Manual Project Saving Feature:**
- 'Save Current Project' button available in multiple locations:
  - Top navigation bar (always visible)
  - Report tab as dedicated 'Save Your Entire Project' button
  - Quick action menu in workspace\n- Clicking 'Save Current Project' button:
  - Prompts user to enter project name (optional, auto-generates if not provided)
  - Saves complete project snapshot including:
    - All datasets in current project
    - All visualizations and charts
    - All dashboards with layouts and filters
    - All ML models and performance reports
    - All SQL queries and Python scripts
    - Data cleaning history and configurations
    - Data modeling relationships
  - Displays success confirmation message
  - Saved project immediately appears in Previous Projects section
- Users can save project at any time without uploading new data
- Multiple save operations create new project versions (not overwrite)
\n**Previous Projects Section:**
- Accessible from:\n  - Home page 'Previous Projects' section
  - Left sidebar navigation item 'Previous Projects' (positioned at end of navigation menu)
- Project list displays:\n  - Project name
  - Creation date and last modified date
  - Number of datasets
  - Number of visualizations created
  - Number of dashboards created
  - Dataset information summary
  - Project thumbnail preview
- Click on any previous project to:\n  - View saved visualizations (read-only mode)
  - View saved dashboards (read-only mode)
  - View ML reports (read-only mode)
  - Reopen project for editing and adding new work
  - Upload additional datasets to existing project
  - Rename project\n  - **Delete project**: Click delete icon/button on project card
    - Displays confirmation dialog: 'Are you sure you want to delete this project? This action cannot be undone.'\n    - Options: 'Delete' (permanently removes project from browser storage) or 'Cancel'\n    - Deleted projects are permanently removed from browser storage
  - Download previous reports and models
- Search and filter options for finding specific projects
- Sort projects by date, name, or activity
\n**Project Isolation:**
- Each project workspace maintains separate data and configurations
- All visualizations, dashboards, and ML models are tied to specific project
- No mixing of data or visualizations between different projects
- Clear separation between current active project and archived previous projects

## 3. Core Features

### 3.1 Data Upload Module

**Supported File Formats:**
- CSV files\n- Excel files (xlsx, xls)
- Excel files with multiple sheets
- TSV files
- JSON files\n- Any delimited text files
\n**Multiple Dataset Upload:**
- Upload multiple datasets simultaneously in a single upload session
- Drag-and-drop multiple files at once
- Browse and select multiple files from file system
- Upload progress indicator for each file
- Batch upload confirmation with list of successfully uploaded datasets
- Option to add more datasets after initial upload without resetting workspace

**Automatic Processing:**
- Automatic file type detection
- Automatic column parsing
- Automatic data type detection (numeric, categorical, date)\n- Display sheet selector for multi-sheet Excel files
\n**Dataset Preview & Modification:**
- Preview first 100 rows of uploaded data\n- View column names, data types, and sample values
- Edit dataset name and add description
- Add tags for easy searching
- View dataset statistics (row count, column count, missing values)
- Modify column properties and metadata
\n### 3.2 Table View Module

**Purpose:**
Table View appears immediately after Upload Data in the workflow, allowing users to select any uploaded dataset, preview it comprehensively, and confirm which dataset they want to work on before performing operations in other modules.

**Core Features:**
- Dataset Selection: Dropdown or list to select from all uploaded datasets in current project
- Full Data Preview: Display complete dataset with scrollable rows and columns (not limited to first 100 rows)
- Schema Inspection: View detailed schema information including:\n  - Column names
  - Data types (integer, float, string, datetime, boolean, etc.)
  - Null/missing value counts per column
  - Unique value counts
  - Sample values for each column
- Column Management:\n  - Rename columns directly in Table View
  - Reorder columns by drag-and-drop
  - Hide/show specific columns
  - Sort data by any column (ascending/descending)
- Data Inspection Tools:
  - Search and filter rows by column values
  - View data statistics (min, max, mean, median for numeric columns)
  - Identify data quality issues (duplicates, outliers, inconsistencies)
- Dataset Confirmation: Confirm selected dataset before proceeding to Data Cleaning, Visualization, or other modules
- Quick Actions:
  - Export selected dataset\n  - Duplicate dataset
  - Delete dataset
  - Refresh data view
\n### 3.3 Data Modeling Engine (Multi-Table Join Capabilities)

**Advanced Visual Data Modeling Interface (Inspired by Power BI & Tableau):**
- **Interactive Canvas with Drag-and-Drop Table Relationship Builder:**
  - Visual representation of table schemas with expandable column lists
  - Click'Add Table' or '+ Table' button to add additional datasets to modeling canvas
  - Select datasets from dropdown list of all uploaded datasets
  - Drag tables onto canvas and arrange them freely
  - Visual connection lines between related tables showing join relationships
  - Color-coded relationship lines indicating join types (Inner/Left/Right/Full/Cross)
  - Hover over relationship lines to view join details and conditions
  - Click on relationship lines to edit or delete joins
  - Zoom in/out and pan across canvas for large data models
  - Mini-map navigator for quick navigation in complex models
  - Auto-layout feature to organize tables automatically
\n- **Smart Relationship Detection:**
  - Automatic detection of potential join keys based on column names and data types
  - Suggested relationships highlighted with dotted lines
  - One-click acceptance of suggested relationships
  - Warning indicators for ambiguous or missing relationships
\n- **Visual Join Configuration Panel:**
  - Side panel displaying join details when relationship is selected
  - Dropdown selectors for join type (Inner/Left/Right/Full/Cross)\n  - Multi-key join support with '+ Add Join Key' button
  - Visual preview of join result with sample data rows
  - Join cardinality indicators (1:1, 1:Many, Many:Many)
  - Filter conditions applicable before join execution
\n- **Table Schema Visualization:**
  - Each table displayed as card with header showing table name and row count
  - Expandable column list showing:\n    - Column names with data type icons
    - Primary key indicators
    - Foreign key indicators
    - Column data type (text, number, date, boolean)\n  - Search functionality within table columns
  - Column highlighting when hovering over join relationships
\n- **Relationship Management:**
  - Create relationships by dragging from one column to another
  - Edit existing relationships by clicking on connection lines
  - Delete relationships with confirmation dialog
  - Duplicate relationships for similar join patterns
  - Save modeling configurations as templates for reuse

**Join Any Number of Tables:**
- Join unlimited tables within a project
- Supported join types:
  - INNER JOIN (only matching rows)
  - LEFT JOIN (all from left + matching from right)
  - RIGHT JOIN (all from right + matching from left)
  - FULL OUTER JOIN (everything from both)\n  - CROSS JOIN (all combinations)
\n**SQL-Based Join Interface:**
- Write custom SQL JOIN queries\n- Syntax highlighting for SQL code
- Autocomplete for table and column names
- Execute and preview join results
- Save SQL join queries for future use
- Support for complex multi-table joins
- Subquery support in join conditions

**Join Configuration Options:**
- Select multiple join keys\n- Handle duplicate column names automatically
- Filter data before or after joining
- Aggregate data during join operations
- Apply transformations during join process
\n**Join Result Management:**
- Preview joined dataset with sample rows before applying\n- Save joined dataset as new dataset in project
- Export joined dataset in various formats
- View join execution statistics (rows matched, unmatched, execution time)
\n**Example Workflow:**
1. Upload both tables (e.g., orders.csv and customers.csv)
2. Go to Data Modeling section
3. Click 'Add Table' or '+ Table' button
4. Select second dataset from dropdown
5. Drag tables onto canvas
6. Drag from orders.customer_id column to customers.id column to create relationship
7. Select join type (Inner/Left/Right/Full/Cross) from dropdown
8. Preview joined result in side panel
9. Apply join to create new combined dataset
10. Save modeling configuration for future use

### 3.4 SQL Query Editor (Full Functional Programming Environment)

**Advanced Editor Features:**
- Syntax highlighting for SQL keywords
- Intelligent autocomplete for:\n  - Table names
  - Column names
  - SQL keywords
  - Functions\n  - Aliases
- Line numbers and code folding
- Multi-line query support
- Error highlighting and validation
- Query formatting and beautification
\n**Comprehensive SQL Operations Support:**
- SELECT, WHERE, GROUP BY, HAVING, ORDER BY\n- Filtering with complex conditions (AND, OR, NOT, IN, BETWEEN, LIKE)\n- Aggregations (SUM, COUNT, AVG, MIN, MAX, STDDEV, VARIANCE)
- Subqueries and nested queries
- CASE statements and conditional logic
- Window functions (ROW_NUMBER, RANK, DENSE_RANK, LAG, LEAD)
- Column transformations (CAST, CONCAT, SUBSTRING, UPPER, LOWER, TRIM)
- Date functions (DATE_ADD, DATE_SUB, DATEDIFF, EXTRACT)
- Schema modifications (ALTER TABLE, ADD COLUMN, DROP COLUMN, RENAME COLUMN)
- Data manipulation (INSERT, UPDATE, DELETE)\n- JOIN operations (INNER, LEFT, RIGHT, FULL, CROSS)
- UNION and UNION ALL operations
\n**Critical Feature: Direct Data Modification**
- All SQL operations (UPDATE, DELETE, INSERT, ALTER) directly modify the actual stored dataset
- Changes made in SQL Editor immediately reflect in:\n  - Table View\n  - Data Cleaning module
  - Visualization Studio
  - Dashboard
  - ML Studio
  - Reports
- Transaction support with rollback capability for safety
- Change history tracking for audit purposes

**Query Execution & Results:**
- Execute button to run queries
- Query result grid with sortable columns
- Pagination for large result sets
- Export query results as CSV or Excel
- View query execution time and performance metrics
- Error messages with line numbers for debugging
- Query history with ability to rerun previous queries
- Result set filtering and searching

**Query Management:**
- Save queries with custom names and descriptions
- Organize queries by project and category
- Share queries via export\n- Version control for query modifications
- Duplicate and modify existing queries
- Add comments and documentation to queries

### 3.5 Python Code Editor (Built-in Fully Functional IDE)

**Comprehensive Python IDE Features:**
- Syntax highlighting for Python code
- Intelligent autocomplete for:
  - Python keywords and built-in functions
  - Pandas functions and methods
  - NumPy functions and operations
  - Scikit-learn modules and classes
  - Matplotlib/Seaborn plotting functions
  - Custom variables and functions
- Line numbers and code folding
- Error highlighting and debugging support
- Code formatting and linting
- Multi-file script support
\n**Supported Python Operations:**
- Data Cleaning: Handle missing values, remove duplicates, fix data types, standardize formats
- Feature Engineering: Create new features, transform existing columns, encode categorical variables, scale numeric features
- Column Transformations: Create, modify, rename, delete columns, apply mathematical operations, string manipulations
- Custom Visualizations: Generate plots using Matplotlib/Seaborn with full customization\n- Statistical Analysis: Descriptive statistics, correlation analysis, hypothesis testing
- Custom Machine Learning: Build and train custom ML models using scikit-learn, TensorFlow, or PyTorch\n- Data Export: Save processed data in various formats, generate custom reports
\n**Critical Feature: Direct Data Modification**\n- All pandas DataFrame operations directly modify the actual stored dataset
- Changes made in Python Editor immediately reflect in:
  - Table View
  - Data Cleaning module
  - Visualization Studio
  - Dashboard
  - ML Studio
  - Reports
- Any operation such as:
  - df.drop() - removes rows/columns from actual dataset
  - df['new_column'] = ... - adds new column to actual dataset
  - df.loc[condition, 'column'] = value - updates values in actual dataset
  - df.merge() - merges datasets and updates storage
  - df.groupby().agg() - creates aggregated dataset
  - df.fillna() - fills missing values in actual dataset
- Automatic synchronization with browser storage after code execution
- Change history tracking for audit purposes
\n**Code Execution Environment:**
- Prominent'Run Code' button to execute Python code
- Execute Python code directly in browser
- Access to uploaded datasets as Pandas DataFrames
- Real-time output display in dedicated output panel below code editor
- View code output and print statements in console
- Display generated plots and visualizations inline in output panel
- Error messages with full traceback information displayed in output panel
- Variable inspector to view current workspace state
- Support for installing additional Python packages
- Clear output option to reset output panel
- Output panel with tabs for 'Console Output' and 'Visualizations'

**Code Management:**
- Save Python scripts with custom names and descriptions
- Organize scripts by project and purpose
- Rerun saved scripts on different datasets
- Export scripts as .py files\n- Version control for script modifications\n- Share scripts via export\n- Add documentation and comments\n
### 3.6 Auto Data Cleaning Pipeline

**Dataset Selection Feature:**
- **Dataset Selection Dropdown:**
  - Located at the top of the Data Cleaning page
  - Lists all datasets uploaded by the user (from Table View / Dataset Manager)
  - Shows currently selected dataset as default
  - Dropdown displays dataset name, row count, and column count for each dataset
\n- **Automatic Refresh on Dataset Selection:**
  - When user selects a dataset from dropdown:\n    - Data Cleaning interface refreshes automatically
    - Dataset Info section updates (name, rows, columns)
    - Selected dataset loads into Python Code Editor
    - Preview table regenerates for selected dataset
    - All cleaning operations apply to newly selected dataset

- **Selection Persistence:**
  - Selected dataset persists when switching between modules (e.g., Data Cleaning → Visualization → back to Data Cleaning)
  - Selection state saved in browser session storage
\n- **Dataset Deletion Handling:**
  - If a dataset is deleted from project, it is automatically removed from dropdown
  - If currently selected dataset is deleted, dropdown resets to first available dataset
  - If no datasets remain, dropdown shows 'No datasets available'

- **Error Handling:**
  - If dataset fails to load, display error message: 'Failed to load dataset. Please try again or select another dataset.'
  - If no datasets exist, show message: 'No datasets uploaded. Please upload a dataset first.'
  - Provide'Retry' button for failed loads

- **UI Styling:**
  - Dropdown follows existing dark theme with purple highlights
  - Selected dataset highlighted with purple accent
  - Hover effects with smooth transitions
  - Clear visual indication of active dataset

**1. Handling Missing Values**
- Remove rows with missing values
- Remove columns with too many missing values
- Impute numeric values using: Mean, Median, Mode, Custom value
- Impute categorical values using: Most frequent value, 'Unknown' placeholder, Forward fill/Backward fill
\n**2. Data Type Conversion**
- Convert Text → Number\n- Convert Text → Date
- Convert Number → Category
- Convert Date → Year/Month/Day/Week\n- Convert Boolean values\n- Fix inconsistent formatting: '1,000' → 1000, date format standardization

**3. Duplicate Handling**
- Identify duplicate rows\n- Remove full duplicates
- Remove partial duplicates using key columns
\n**4. Outlier Treatment**
- Detect outliers using: Z-score, IQR (Interquartile Range)\n- Remove outliers\n- Cap outliers (Winsorization)
- Replace with median\n\n**5. Text Cleaning**
- Trim whitespace
- Convert to lowercase/uppercase
- Remove special characters\n- Remove extra spaces
- Replace unwanted characters
- Standardize category names (e.g., 'Male', 'male', 'M' → 'Male')
\n**6. Column Cleaning**
- Rename columns
- Remove special characters from headers
- Drop unnecessary columns
- Drop ID columns (if unique identifier)
- Extract useful info: Split column by delimiter, Extract domain from email, Extract numbers/text\n
**7. Date & Time Cleaning**
- Convert strings to datetime\n- Extract: Year, Month, Quarter, Day of Week, Hour\n- Create: Time difference columns, Age from DOB
- Standardize timezone if needed

**8. Numeric Corrections**
- Convert currency strings → number ('₹1,20,000' → 120000)
- Fix negative values if invalid
- Normalize/scale numbers: Min-Max scaling, Standardization

**9. Categorical Cleaning**
- Merge similar categories ('Hyderabad', 'Hyd', 'HYD' → 'Hyderabad')
- Encode categories: Label Encoding, One-hot Encoding
\n**10. Handling Invalid Data**
- Remove rows with impossible values: Negative age, Zero salary
- Validate formats (email, phone, pin code)
- Remove corrupted data
\n**11. Feature Engineering (Optional)**
- Create new useful columns\n- Bucket numeric values: Age groups, Salary bands
- Flag important patterns\n- Calculate ratios, differences

**Output:**
- Cleaning Report (downloadable as PDF or Word)\n\n### 3.7 Visualization Studio

**Dataset Selection Feature:**
- **Dataset Selection Dropdown:**
  - Located at the top of the Visualization page
  - Lists all datasets uploaded by the user\n  - Shows currently selected dataset as default
  - Dropdown displays dataset name, row count, and column count for each dataset

- **Automatic Refresh on Dataset Selection:**
  - When user selects a dataset from dropdown:
    - Visualization interface refreshes automatically
    - Available columns update based on selected dataset
    - Chart configuration options update to reflect new dataset schema
    - All visualization operations apply to newly selected dataset\n
- **Selection Persistence:**
  - Selected dataset persists when switching between modules\n  - Selection state saved in browser session storage

- **UI Styling:**
  - Dropdown follows existing dark theme with teal/purple highlights
